Product name: Victorian Love Token Bracelet, Antique Coin bracelet, Love Token Coins, Silver Antique Charm bracelet, 1800s Jewelry, Estate Jewelry, Charms
Description:
Our Victorian Love Token Charm Bracelet was created with love using coins that date as far back as 1875. Back in the days before the Mall or gift stores when family and loved ones offered gifts of the heart. These authentic antique coins have been sanded, smoothed and engraved with personal messages of initials and tiny birds. One coin is engraved with a bird sitting in the rain holding an umbrella.
There are seven coins in all on this bracelet and one that I find to be quite fascinating with initials engraved into the open pages of a book. The 8-1/2'' buckle style bracelet is 3/8'' wide. It can be fastened at 2 levels and retains its original slide clasp. This circa 1877 bracelet is hand made from a thin band of silver and embellished with simple etchings.
This precious Victorian keepsake has not been polished and exhibits age appropriate wear. I would love to keep this for myself.

Product name: Indigo Dye Vat Collection, Pre Reduced Indigo, Henna, and Lime
Description:
Dyeing fibre with indigo is a magical experience. Gently heat your indigo vat ingredients in water and watch the bath turn from blue to pale greenish yellow as the oxygen is removed. Dip your fibres in and watch them change from greenish yellow to indigo blue as they get exposed to oxygen. I never get tired of seeing the transformation! 
This kit includes:
10g of pre reduced indigo
20g of henna 
30g of lime (calcium hydroxide)
Each comes in a glass jar.
All you need is water, natural fibres of your choice, and a pot to get an indigo vat going!
Although no mordant is needed for indigo dyeing, indigo must be combined with something to increase the pH (lime) and something to remove all the oxygen from the dye vat (henna). This will allow the indigo to become water soluble and adhere to the fibre. 
10g of indigo (along with 20g of henna and 30g of lime) will dye ~1200g of fibre a pale to medium shade and 600g fibre a medium to dark shade. 
As with most natural dyes, the colours will be stronger on protein fibres such as wool or silk. Indigo on cellulose fibres like cotton and linen tend to be paler and more subdued. Synthetic fibres tend not to take up natural dyes.
* This listing only includes the packets of natural dyestuff and instruction. It does not include the yarn pictured, which is shown to give an idea of possible colours).

Description:
White Birch Fireplace Logs!  6 Piece Set! SHIPPING IS INCLUDED IN THE PRICE!!
Our Decorative White Birch Logs are harvested in Northern Wisconsin.  The White Birch has an exfoliating “paper-type” bark. The white birch bark is white with black markings and can have a mixture of colors such as cream, brown and caramel.
Not every birch tree looks the same and the photos shown are examples. What we do with each set of logs is take the variations and match them so that each set of logs look like they belong together. Please note that colors and variations may vary from set to set.  Each set of birch logs also have a mixture of diameters ranging from the 2 inch to 3 inch.
These logs are all natural and have not been treated or preserved with chemicals or insecticides. These logs have not been "touched up" and may have natural "scuffs and scratches".
